
Problem Story (Intuition Building)
Imagine you have a string s and you want to create exactly k palindrome strings using all its characters.

👉 A palindrome is a string that reads the same forward and backward
(e.g., aa, aba, c)

## Goal
Check whether it is possible to divide characters of s into exactly k palindromes

## Key Observations
🔹 1. Minimum Requirement
Each palindrome must have at least 1 character

So:
if(n < k) → impossible
🔹 2. Role of Odd Frequency Characters
👉 Important rule:
  A palindrome can have:
  0 odd characters (even length palindrome like abba)
  1 odd character (center in aba)
👉 So:

Each odd frequency character needs its own palindrome
🔥 Core Idea

Count how many characters have odd frequency

Let:

oddCount = number of characters with odd frequency
📌 Condition to Form k Palindromes
oddCount <= k <= n
Why?
✔️ Case 1: oddCount > k
Too many odd characters
Each needs separate palindrome
Not enough k
❌ Impossible
✔️ Case 2: oddCount <= k
You can:
Use odd chars as centers
Distribute remaining chars to form more palindromes
✅ Possible

👉 So answer = true
💻 Final Code Logic Summary
Step-by-step:
If n < k → return false
Count frequency using HashMap
Count oddCount
If oddCount > k → false
Else → true

⏱ Complexity
Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Comlexity: O(1) (since only 26 lowercase letters possible)

//----------------------------------------------------------------------Code-------------------------------------------------------------//
class Solution {
    public boolean canConstruct(String s, int k) {
        int n = s.length();

        if(n < k){
            return false;
        }
        if(n == k){
            return true;
        }

        HashMap<Character,Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
        for(int i=0; i<n; i++){
            if(!map.containsKey(s.charAt(i))){
                map.put(s.charAt(i), 1);
            }
            else{
                map.put(s.charAt(i), map.get(s.charAt(i)) + 1);
            }
        }

        int oddCount = 0;

        for(int freq : map.values()){
            if(freq % 2 != 0){
                oddCount++;
            }
        }

        if(oddCount > k){
            return false;
        }
        return true;
    }
}
